Following the exploration of the main effects of pubertal development and strain, the analysis turned to examining interactions. Specifically, the joint effects of pubertal development and strain on delinquent outcomes were examined. Table 2
 displays the results from four distinct regression equations, which test the interactive effects of general strain and pubertal development on violent and overall offending for both males and females. The results lend support to Hypothesis 1, which predicts that early pubertal development will significantly increase the effect of general strain on deviant outcomes. For males, this appears to be the case for both violent and overall delinquency, as both coefficients are statistically significant in the predicted direction (β = .093, significant at p ≤ .01; β = .059, significant at p ≤ .05). In short, the results indicate that advanced pubertal development among males exacerbated the effects of general strain on both violent and overall delinquency (see Figure 1
).
